                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d647">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">760F.62/1135: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-09-27T11:00:00+01:00"
                            >September 27, 1938—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received September 27—9:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1604. The British Ambassador has just informed me in greatest confidence that
                    Hitler’s reply to the two notes from Chamberlain presented to him by Horace
                    Wilson was the most violent outburst possible; that nothing could have been more
                    unhelpful than Hitler’s <pb facs="0682" n="674" xml:id="pg_674"/> response. He
                    added very privately that nevertheless Horace Wilson expected to see Hitler
                    again this morning.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bullitt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
